These ‘ Instantiae Luctae’ or ‘wrestling instances' (as they are best called) comprise what Bacon conceived to be the various conflicting kinds oi motion. The discussion, as well as his use of the tenu ‘Motion,' will often be found to be vague and unsatisfactory. The indestructibility os matter (‘ motus antitypiae materiae ’l and even the property oi inertia itsell l‘motus decubitus, sive motus exhorrentiae motus ’l are included by him under this generic name. Motion, l need hardly say, ought, strictly speaking, to be used in the sense of ‘change ol place,’ though it may legitimately be applied to changes in the relative positions of the parts ol a body (tor instance, ol the molecules) as well as to changes of place of the entire body itself. The vague use oi the term ‘ Motion ’ dates from Aristotle downwards. Aquinas, in the Summa, repeatedly says that any operation whatever may ‘ secundum similitudinem’ be called motion.
